  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="ENG">Strengthening Civil Courage &#x2013; External Stress Factors / International Lobby and Advocacy</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="ENG">In the Strengthening Civil Courage programme, the pillar of work called External Stress Factors (ESF) is aimed primarily at taking away stress factors that are external to the conflict. The conflicts in which the alliance is seeking to implement its programme have a myriad of external stress factors. For the international lobby and advocacy component of the work on external stress factors, the alliance seeks to address the factors caused by two types of actors: states and companies. Impact through environmental factors is also part of the programme.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="ENG">The activity is part of a larger programme implemented by the Strengthening Civil Courage Alliance, consisting of ABAAD &#x2013; Resource Center for Gender Equality, Amnesty International The Netherlands, DefendDefenders, PAX and their partner networks.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="ENG">The main objective for this programme is that states, companies and other actors contribute to effective international standards which protect people against harm caused through the effects of weapons, business activities in conflict-affected areas or environmental impacts of conflict. More specifically, the programme aims for states to contribute to effective international standards regulating the use of and trade in (controversial) weapons; and, for companies to adhere to effective international standards that prevent and mitigate human rights impacts of businesses in conflict. Lastly, the programme aims to address and mitigate environmental impact of warfare.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="ENG">The programme targets states, the Dutch government, the UN and multilateral bodies, arms companies, affected communities, financial institutions, multinational companies, and consumers in Western countries.</narrative>
  </description>
